# Candidate Law Families — KIRC-smoke (ccRCC, VHL–HIF axis)

## 1. HIF-activation contrast
**Law:** `score ≈ log(CA9 / AGXT)`
**Rationale:** VHL loss stabilizes HIF, inducing CA9 while clear-cell transformation displaces normal proximal-tubule identity (AGXT), so the ratio captures "HIF-on vs tubule-identity-off" in one axis.
**Skeptic test:** Permute AGXT labels across samples; if the ratio's separation survives, the denominator is cosmetic and the law reduces to CA9 alone.

## 2. Pseudohypoxic glycolysis balance
**Law:** `score ≈ log(LDHA · VEGFA) − log(ALB)`
**Rationale:** HIF simultaneously drives glycolysis (LDHA) and angiogenesis (VEGFA) while tumor cachexia/liver-axis suppression lowers ALB, giving a two-up/one-down balance.
**Skeptic test:** Drop either LDHA or VEGFA; if AUC is unchanged, the "co-activation" claim is unsupported and only one HIF target is doing the work.

## 3. Tubule-identity loss (single-feature null)
**Law:** `score ≈ −AGXT`  (or `1/AGXT`)
**Rationale:** AGXT is a proximal-tubule marker lost in ccRCC regardless of HIF state, so a one-feature law may already saturate performance.
**Skeptic test:** Compare against all multi-feature families above with a complexity penalty; if Δperformance < small ε, reject the more complex laws.

## 4. Angiogenic–metabolic interaction
**Law:** `score ≈ √(VEGFA · LDHA) / AGXT`
**Rationale:** Geometric mean of two HIF-downstream programs (vascular + glycolytic) normalized by tubule identity encodes the canonical ccRCC 
